<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 5:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27171b70630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>5.</label.designator><headtext>Admission and Exclusion of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7ad4682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>5:1.</label.designator><headtext>Admissibility</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>With adoption of <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-1-104" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ic41ed2d074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-1-104</cite.query>, the Georgia legislature shifted the role of deciding preliminary questions of fact that affect the admissibility of evidence to the judge rather than the jury. <eos/><bos/>Former O.C.G.A. § 24-9-7 was not specifically carried over into the new Evidence Code. <eos/><bos/>This realignment brings Georgia law in line with <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER104" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Ic41ed2d174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 104</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Thus, the courts should use a preponderance of the evidence standard in deciding preliminary questions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77fa5f4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] In making its determination, the court shall not be bound by the rules of evidence, except for those with respect to privileges.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77fa5f4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The judge&apos;s finding on an issue of fact will stand on appeal if there is any evidence to support it.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77fa5f4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference><?page no="139"?>] The admission of inadmissible evidence, over objection, will not ordinarily be ground for reversal, as the appellate court will presume that the judge disregarded the inadmissible evidence and based his finding only on admissible evidence.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77fa5f4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I77fa5f4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="2042886583" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic41ef9e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Anglin v. State, 302 Ga. 333, 806 S.E.2d 573 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77fa5f4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="2044331735" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic41f480274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hendrix v. State, 303 Ga. 525, 813 S.E.2d 339 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77fa5f4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1949105147" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic41fe44274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Madison v. Montgomery, 206 Ga. 199, 56 S.E.2d 292 (1949)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1964125869" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic41fe44574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Powell v. Commercial Travelers Mut. Acc. Ass&apos;n of America, 110 Ga. App. 54, 137 S.E.2d 759 (1964)</cite.query><?page no="139"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77fa5f4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1964125810" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216ae274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Nelliger v. Atlanta Baggage &amp; Cab Co., 109 Ga. App. 863, 137 S.E.2d 566 (1964)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1976144114" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216ae574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sanchez v. Walker County Dept. of Family and Children Services, 138 Ga. App. 49, 225 S.E.2d 441 (1976)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1976136112" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216ae874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">237 Ga. 406, 229 S.E.2d 66 (1976)</cite.query> (disapproved of <case.history>on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1996040137" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216aeb74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">In Interest of R.D.F., 266 Ga. 294, 466 S.E.2d 572 (1996)</cite.query>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1985100892" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216aee74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Cannon v. Boesger, 172 Ga. App. 488, 323 S.E.2d 687 (1984)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>However, the juvenile court judge may not base his decision on hearsay. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1980193564" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216af174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wooten v. Department of Human Resources, 152 Ga. App. 304, 262 S.E.2d 583 (1979)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1964125810" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216af474d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Nelliger</ital></cite.query> case was approved in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1979106280" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216af774d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Citizens &amp; Southern Bank of Dublin v. Morris State Bldg. Corp., 243 Ga. 169, 253 S.E.2d 89 (1979)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The bench trial rule also applies to the juvenile court in a deprivation hearing. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018132" w-serial-number="1979106324" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ic4216afa74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Dawley v. Butts County Dept. of Family &amp; Children Services, 148 Ga. App. 815, 253 S.E.2d 235 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 5:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
